**Addendum 01 - Background on CAOCIT**
[[div class="quote-block"]]

**-- [Beginning of Relevant Section] --**

**Dr. ##red|██████ ████##:** ...and that recursive cycle of amplification is how we're able to use this technology to search for deep space waveforms with 10x more clarity than the current leading satellite system in the world. We've found some very interesting, albeit hard to decipher, signals in the so-called "void" of space.

**Prof. ##red|███ ██████████##:** Great, now, I want to move on to the other piece of technology your team worked on; I don't have the document number but I believe your boss referred to them as "Time Boxes". Tell me about the research you're doing with those.

**Dr. ##red|████##:** Yeah, sorry about that, the name Time Box is still a placeholder, MCD[[footnote]] Methodical Colloquialism Division [[/footnote]] is working on a more formal one at the moment. Oh, but sorry, to answer your question, Time Boxes are essentially the main power behind CAOCIT, they're what let us do all this long-term analysis so seamlessly.

**Prof. ##red|██████████##:** How are they, functionally?

**Dr. ##red|████##:** Well, technically speaking, they're great! Most of the time, we'll hook up a computer to run for a few trillion years, consolidate its own data, and then reset the chamber automatically, so usually with only one Time Box, we can get a few septillion years of data analysis within an hour. 

**Prof. ##red|██████████##:** That sounds... almost impossible to believe. And you have the data storage capacity to handle this?

**Dr. ##red|████##:** Oh sure, data's the least of our problems. We spend far more time sanitizing than anything - when you're dealing with time on a pseudo-universal scale, stuff can get nasty really quick. We learned the hard way with Site-##red|██## that if you leave so much as a piece of lint in a Time Box, that sucker will black hole in an instant. 

**Prof. ##red|██████████##:** That much from just a piece of dust? I mean, do you have any precautions in place against, for example, getting a researcher trapped inside one during testing? From what it sounds like, if you let a second pass by before turning it off, you'd be far too late.

**Dr. ##red|████##:** Well... we've done some smaller things like putting a person inside of one and setting it to an hour, but it's not as simple as "an hour passes inside the box". The reality actually changes to adapt to what are essentially new laws of... well, reality. Limited experimentation has revealed some very intriguing effects of what being in that sort of reality can do to the human mind. Paranoia, delusions, and fear are all pretty common.  

**Prof. ##red|██████████##:** Would someone inside be able to disable it themselves?

**Dr. ##red|████##:** It's not super clear if they'd even want to; you experience time much differently while inside one, but from a practical standpoint, I don't see why not, after all, computers obviously work just fine. Plus it's not like we spend too much time inside of them ourselves. The only rooms that need a lot of personal maintenance are the calibration rooms, and we usually only hook those up to run for like three or four years max. 

**Prof. ##red|██████████##:** Calibration? So, what, you just feed these computers a giant dataset and run it to see what it comes up with?

**Dr. ##red|████##:** That's how I'd explain it if I was in a hurry, but in reality, there are actually three computers per setup - one to do the primary analysis, one to do the production, and one to compare what computer two makes to the primary dataset, and filter what it deems fit back into computer one. Hence the "Cyclical" in CAOCIT. 

**Prof. ##red|██████████##:** //(taking notes)// Interesting.

**-- [End of Relevant Section] --**


[[/div]]

-----
**Addendum 02 - Examples of ##red|███##-3955**

The following audio files are taken from the database of CRYSTAL-INE, a general purpose AI at Site-##red|██##, during CAOCIT procedural testing. In all three, ##red|███##-3955 is audible underneath the melody.

